04175nam a22005535i 9780804778886DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047788867 a10.1515/97808047788862doi  a(DE-B1597)564475  a(OCoLC)1198930536  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPL833.I95bZ735 2012 7aLIT0080302bisacsh04a895.6/144a895.61441 aLong, Hoyt, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Uneven Ground :bMiyazawa Kenji and the Making of Place in Modern Japan /cHoyt Long. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Naming -- tPrologue, Making Place for the Author -- tChapter One. Finding Value in Locality -- tChapter Two. Decentering the Uneven Geography of Cultural Production -- tChapter Three. Toward a Provincializing Literary Production -- tChapter Four. Making Space for a New Literary Region -- tChapter Five. Conversations with Nature -- tChapter Six. Performing the Village Square -- tChapter Seven. Farmers' Art in an Age of Cosmopolitan Agrarianism -- tEpilogue. Trading Places -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of literary and artistic production in modern Japan has typically centered on the literature and art of Tokyo, yet cultural activity in the country's regional cities and rural towns was no less vibrant. On Uneven Ground recovers pieces of this neglected history through the figure of Miyazawa Kenji (1896-1933). While alive, he remained a mostly unknown and unread provincial author whose experiments with narrative fiction, amateur theater, and farmer's art reveal an intense determination to reimagine and remake his native place, in the northeast of Japan, meaningful. Today, Miyazawa is one of the most recognized figures in Japan's modern literary canon. The story of his radical posthumous rise presents an opportunity to examine the larger history of how writing and other forms of artistic practice have intersected with place-based identity and the uneven geography of cultural production. The first book-length study of Miyazawa in English, On Uneven Ground centers on Miyazawa's life and writing to recreate a sense of what it was to write about and remake place from a spatially marginal position in the cultural field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aJapanese literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aJapanese literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aLiterature and societyzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804778886zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778886423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778886.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles